          log.warn("Waiting for timestamp from Oracle. Is it running? waitTotal={}s waitPeriod={}s",

First there is a check to see if the timeout is positive (do we want to accept a value of 1?)

      int timeout = env.getConfiguration().getConnectionRetryTimeout();
      if (timeout < 0) {

In this block, if there is no positive value for the timeout, the values are assigned and an exponential backoff of 2^x is used until we have waited 60 seconds and then we warn out again

      if (timeout < 0) {
        long waitPeriod = 1;
        long waitTotal = 0;
        while (!tr.cdl.await(waitPeriod, TimeUnit.SECONDS)) {
          checkClosed();
          waitTotal += waitPeriod;
          if (waitPeriod < MAX_ORACLE_WAIT_PERIOD) {
            waitPeriod *= 2;
          }
          log.warn("Waiting for timestamp from Oracle. Is it running? waitTotal={}s waitPeriod={}s",
              waitTotal, waitPeriod);

Now if there was a good positive value from the Config then we bypass the exponential back off and go here, wait one time, and complete. All of these are using count down latch functions to wait (just to show understanding of code).

      } else if (!tr.cdl.await(timeout, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS)) {
        throw new FluoException("Timed out (after " + timeout
            + "ms) trying to retrieve timestamp from Oracle.  Is the Oracle running?");
